Study on measuring burden of disease.

Pang L(1), Jin SG, Song GD, Guo ZY.

Author information:
(1)North China Coal Medical Collage, Tangshan, Hebei.

DALY (Disability Adjusted Life Years) was recommended as a new indicator to 
measure burden of disease (BOD). Although BOD combines information from both 
morbidity and mortality, it only reflects the burden from the patients 
themselves because of their illness or death. As a common indicator, BOD should 
not only include the burden from the patients, but also the burden to the 
society around the patients, such as the input and support from the society to 
the ill person, and the losses from the related events. The aim of this study is 
to explore the scope and the magnitude of the burden to the society using stroke 
as an example. Results show that the burden due to time lost for caring for 
patients in hospitals accounts for 2.4% of total BOD (in a narrow sense), which 
indicates that BOD may be underestimated if the burden to the society is 
ignored.

